{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01M9goudWgFP3Gwtec6Yn9i7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The openssl-toolbox pod doesn't exist yet. I need to create it. Let me think about the approach:\n\n1. Create an openssl-toolbox pod for certificate generation\n2. Generate CA certificate and node/client certificates\n3. Store them as Kubernetes secrets\n4. Update the StatefulSet to use TLS (remove --insecure flag, add --certs-dir flag, mount the certs secret)\n5. Restart the pods\n\nLet me plan the certificate structure needed for CockroachDB:\n- CA certificate (ca.crt, ca.key)\n- Node certificates for each node (node.crt, node.key) covering all node DNS names\n- Client certificate for root user (client.root.crt, client.root.key)\n\nThe certs need to be organized in the /cockroach/cockroach-certs directory with ca.crt, node.crt, node.key, client.root.crt, and client.root.key. For the node certificate, I need to include all the DNS names for the nodes.\n\nI'm listing out the SANs needed: localhost, 127.0.0.1, and the Kubernetes service DNS names for each pod in the StatefulSet plus the headless and public service endpoints. Rather than creating individual certs per node, I'll generate a single certificate with all these SANs to keep things simpler. Now I need to create an openssl toolbox pod to generate these certificates, create the Kubernetes secrets, and update the StatefulSet to use them. The readiness probe needs to switch to HTTPS for the health check endpoint in secure mode. Now I'll set up the openssl-toolbox pod to generate the certificates.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":115,"cache_read_input_tokens":31102,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":115},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"cont